    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-04-19T07:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-04-19T07:00:00-05:00" n="738"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d738">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">760i.61/111: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Estonia</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_LER1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Leonard</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tallinn</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-04-19T14:00:00+02:00"
                            >April 19, 1939—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received April 19—10:34 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>13. I have inquired from the Minister of Foreign Affairs<note n="83"
                        xml:id="d738fn83">
                        <persName corresp="#p_SK2">Karl Selter</persName>.</note> concerning rumored
                    assistance to Estonia offered by Soviet Government and was confidentially
                    furnished with copies of a communication to the Estonian Minister at Moscow
                    dated March 28th indicating that Russia could not remain passive if the
                    independence of Estonia were restricted either freely or through outside
                    pressure, to which on April 7th Estonian Government replied it could never
                    consent to any restriction of its sovereignty but that to it alone belonged the
                    right to judge when its rights were infringed, and that it could not share with
                    any other state the right and duty to care for its neutrality and its
                        independence.<note n="84" xml:id="d738fn84">The American Chargé in Moscow,
                        in commenting upon this Soviet <hi rend="italic">démarche</hi> in his
                        despatch No. 2285, April 26, 1939, stated that since there had been no
                        positive result “its chief importance lies in the fact that it reveals the
                        strategic importance which the Soviet Union attaches to the Baltic States
                        bordering on its frontiers”, and that as far as was known no similar
                        approach had been made to Lithuania. (740.00/1517)</note> Despatch
                        follows<note n="85" xml:id="d738fn85">Despatch No. 84, April 25, not
                        printed.</note> in the pouch enclosing above-mentioned copies of
                    communications.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_LER1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Leonard</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
